<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="517" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,289,2025]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1929,1954]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Etymology.</emphasis>
The stem 
<emphasis box="[453,525,1929,1953]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">arche-</emphasis>
of the proposed new name is derived from the Greek adjective archaios (in Latin 
<emphasis box="[151,239,1965,1989]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">archeos</emphasis>
)—old, ancient, combined with the name of the closely related genus 
<emphasis box="[1043,1173,1965,1989]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Hellerenius</emphasis>
, to underline the more plesiotypic set of characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
